WEBVTT

00:23.700 --> 00:28.400
CHAPTER 1 ECONOMY

00:29.500 --> 00:50.380
When I wrote the following pages, or rather the bulk of them, I lived alone, in the woods, a mile from any neighbor, in a house which I had built myself on the shore of Walden Pond, in Concord, Massachusetts, and earned my living by the labor of my hands only.

00:50.380 --> 00:58.960
I lived there two years and two months. At present I am a sojourner in civilized life again.

00:59.680 --> 01:20.240
I should not uptrude my affairs so much on the notice of my readers, if very particular inquiries had not been made by my townsmen concerning my mode of life, which some would call impertinent, though they do not appear to me at all impertinent, but considering the circumstances very natural and pertinent.

01:21.160 --> 01:38.740
Some have asked what I got to eat, if I did not feel lonesome, if I was not afraid, and the like. Others have been curious to learn what portion of my income I devoted to charitable purposes, and some, who have large families, how many poor children I maintained.

01:39.740 --> 01:48.860
I will therefore ask those of my readers who feel no particular interest in me to pardon me if I undertake to answer some of these questions in this book.

01:49.840 --> 02:00.520
In most books the I, or first person, is omitted. In this it will be retained. That, in respect to egotism, is the main difference.

02:01.300 --> 02:19.360
We commonly do not remember that it is, after all, always the first person that is speaking. I should not talk so much about myself, if there were anybody else, whom I knew as well. Unfortunately I am confined to this theme by the narrowness of my experience.

02:20.940 --> 02:45.760
Moreover I, on my side, require of every writer, first or last, a simple and sincere account of his own life, and not merely what he has heard of other men's lives, some such account as he would send to his kindred from a distant land, for if he has lived sincerely it must have been in a distant land to me.

02:46.720 --> 03:07.040
Perhaps these pages are more particularly addressed to poor students. As for the rest of my readers, they will accept such portions as apply to them. I trust that none will stretch the seams in putting on the coat, for it may do good service to him whom it fits.

03:09.080 --> 03:34.920
I would feign say something, not so much concerning the Chinese and sandwich islanders as you who read these pages, who are said to live in New England, something about your condition, especially your outward condition or circumstances in this world, in this town, what it is, whether it is necessary that it be as bad as it is, whether it cannot be improved as well as not.

03:34.920 --> 03:48.660
I have travelled a good deal in Concord, and everywhere, in shops and offices and fields, the inhabitants have appeared to me to be doing penance in a thousand remarkable ways.

03:49.300 --> 04:11.320
What I have heard of Brahmins, sitting exposed to four fires and looking in the face of the sun, or hanging suspended with their heads downward over flames, or looking at the heavens over their shoulders, until it becomes impossible for them to resume their natural position, while from the twist of the neck nothing but liquids can pass into their stomach,

04:12.020 --> 04:24.680
or dwelling chained for life at the foot of a tree, or measuring with their bodies like caterpillars the breadth of vast empires, or standing on one leg on the top of pillars.

04:25.880 --> 04:32.920
Even these forms of conscious penance are hardly more incredible and astonishing than the scenes which I daily witness.

04:33.640 --> 04:49.220
The twelve labours of Hercules were trifling in comparison with those which my neighbours have undertaken, for they were only twelve and had an end, but I could never see that these men slew or captured any monster or finished any labour.

04:50.000 --> 04:59.700
They had no friend, Aeolus, to burn with a hot iron the root of the Hydra's head, but as soon as one head is crushed, two spring up.

05:00.800 --> 05:14.600
I see young men, my townsmen, whose misfortune it is to have inherited farms, houses, barns, cattle, and farming tools, for these are more easily acquired than got rid of.

05:15.160 --> 05:23.920
Better if they had been born in the open pasture and suckled by a wolf, that they might have seen with clearer eyes what field they were called to labour in.

05:24.880 --> 05:34.560
Who made them serfs of the soil? Why should they eat their sixty acres, when man is condemned to eat only his peck of dirt?

05:35.660 --> 05:39.340
Why should they begin digging their graves as soon as they are born?

05:40.340 --> 05:47.540
They have got to live a man's life, pushing all these things before them, and get on as well as they can.

05:48.660 --> 06:11.760
How many a poor, immortal soul have I met well nigh crushed and smothered under its load, creeping down the road of life, pushing before it a barn seventy-five feet by forty, its Augean stables never cleansed, and one hundred acres of land, tillage, mowing, pasture, and woodlot,

06:12.840 --> 06:23.060
The portionless, who struggle with no such unnecessary inherited encumbrances, find it labour enough to subdue and cultivate a few cubic feet of flesh.

06:24.340 --> 06:32.360
But men labour under a mistake. The better part of the man is soon ploughed into the soil for compost.

06:33.600 --> 06:46.920
By a seeming fate, commonly called necessity, they are employed, as it says in an old book, laying up treasures, which moth and rust will corrupt, and thieves break through and steal.

06:46.920 --> 06:53.640
It is a fool's life, as they will find when they get to the end of it, if not before.

06:54.820 --> 07:02.160
It is said that Deusalian and Pyrrha created men by throwing stones over their heads behind them.

07:02.160 --> 07:18.600
Indigenus durum sumus experienci levorum, e documenta damus qua simus origin nati, or, as Raleigh rhymes it in his sonorous way,

07:20.280 --> 07:30.840
From fence our kind heart-hearted is, enduring pain and care, approving that our bodies of a stony nature are.

07:32.380 --> 07:39.540
So much for a blind obedience to a blundering oracle, throwing the stones over their heads behind them, and not seeing where they fell.

07:40.600 --> 07:58.320
Most men, even in this comparatively free country, through mere ignorance and mistake, are so occupied with the factitious cares and superfluously coarse labours of life that its finer fruits cannot be plucked by them.

07:58.940 --> 08:05.440
Their fingers, from excessive toil, are too clumsy and tremble too much for that.

08:06.260 --> 08:12.640
Actually, the labouring man has not leisure for a true integrity day by day.

08:13.280 --> 08:18.100
He cannot afford to sustain the manliest relations to men.

08:19.020 --> 08:21.680
His labour would be depreciated in the market.

08:22.980 --> 08:25.840
He has no time to be anything but a machine.

08:25.840 --> 08:36.640
How can he remember well his ignorance, which his growth requires, who has so often to use his knowledge?

08:38.160 --> 08:45.800
We should feed and clothe him gratuitously sometimes, and recruit him with our cordials, before we judge of him.

08:46.600 --> 08:56.480
The finest qualities of our nature, like the bloom on fruits, can be preserved only by the most delicate handling.

08:57.580 --> 09:02.420
Yet we do not treat ourselves, nor one another, thus tenderly.

09:03.920 --> 09:12.460
Some of you, we all know, are poor, find it hard to live, or sometimes, as it were, gasping for breath.

09:12.460 --> 09:20.060
I have no doubt that some of you who read this book are unable to pay for all the dinners which you have actually eaten,

09:20.580 --> 09:33.020
or for the coats and shoes which are fast wearing or already worn out, and have come to this page to spend borrowed or stolen time, robbing your creditors of an hour.

09:33.020 --> 09:42.020
It is very evident what mean and sneaking lives many of you live, for my sight has been whetted by experience.

09:43.540 --> 09:53.420
Always on the limits, trying to get into business, trying to get out of debt, a very ancient slow, called by the Latins,

09:53.420 --> 10:07.640
Ais alienum, another's brass, for some of their coins were made of brass, still living and dying and buried by this other's brass,

10:07.640 --> 10:23.160
always promising to pay, promising to pay tomorrow, and dying today, insolvent, seeking to curry favor, to get custom, by how many modes, only not state prison offenses,

10:24.220 --> 10:35.060
lying, flattering, voting, contracting yourself into a nutshell of civility, or dilating into an atmosphere of thin and vaporous generosity,

10:35.480 --> 10:43.840
that you may persuade your neighbor to let you make his shoes or his hat or his coat or his carriage or import his groceries for him,

10:43.840 --> 10:57.920
making yourself sick, that you may lay up something against a sick day, something to be tucked away in an old chest, or in a stocking behind the plastering, or more safely in the brick bank,

10:58.780 --> 11:03.680
no matter where, no matter how much, or how little.

11:04.800 --> 11:18.680
I sometimes wonder that we can be so frivolous, I may almost say, as to attend to the gross but somewhat foreign form of servitude called Negro slavery,

11:18.680 --> 11:37.640
there are so many keen and subtle masters that enslave both North and South, it is hard to have a Southern overseer, it is worse to have a Northern one, but worst of all when you are the slave driver of yourself.

11:39.160 --> 11:54.560
Talk of a divinity in man? Look at the teamster on the highway, wending to market by day or night. Does any divinity stir within him, his highest duty to fodder and water his horses?

11:54.560 --> 12:18.320
What is his destiny to him compared with the shipping interests? Does not he drive for squire makester? How godlike, how immortal is he? See how he cowers and sneaks, how vaguely all the day he fears not being immortal nor divine,

12:18.320 --> 12:42.300
but the slave and prisoner of his own opinion of himself, a fame won by his own deeds. Public opinion is a weak tyrant compared with our own private opinion. What a man thinks of himself, that it is which determines, or rather indicates, his fate.

12:44.940 --> 13:11.280
Self-emancipation, even in the West Indian provinces of the fancy and imagination, what Wilberforce is there to bring that about? Think also of the ladies of the land weaving toilet cushions against the last day not to betray too green an interest in their fates, as if you could kill time without injuring eternity.

13:11.280 --> 13:34.060
The mass of men lead lives of quiet desperation. What is called resignation is confirmed desperation. From the desperate city you go into the desperate country and have to console yourself with the bravery of minks and muskrats.

13:35.260 --> 13:55.580
A stereotyped but unconscious despair is concealed even under what are called the games and amusements of mankind. There is no play in them, for this comes after work. But it is a characteristic of wisdom not to do desperate things.

13:56.860 --> 14:14.980
When we consider what, to use the words of the catechism, is the chief end of man, and what are the true necessaries and means of life, it appears as if men had deliberately chosen the common mode of living because they preferred it to any other.

14:14.980 --> 14:36.600
Yet they honestly think there is no choice left. But alert and healthy natures remember that the sun rose clear. It is never too late to give up our prejudices. No way of thinking or doing however ancient can be trusted without proof.

14:37.720 --> 14:54.940
What everyone echoes, or in silence passes by as true today, may turn out to be falsehood to morrow, mere smoke of opinion, which some had trusted for a cloud that would sprinkle fertilizing rain on their fields.

14:55.980 --> 15:09.180
What old people say you cannot do, you try and find that you can. Old deeds for old people, and new deeds for new.

15:10.620 --> 15:32.600
Old people did not know enough once, perchance, to fetch fresh fuel to keep the fire a-going. New people put a little dry wood under a pot, and our world round the globe with the speed of birds, in a way to kill old people, as the phrase is.

15:32.600 --> 15:52.320
Age is no better, hardly so well qualified for an instructor as youth, for it has not profited so much as it has lost. One may almost doubt if the wisest man has learned anything of absolute value by living.

15:53.440 --> 16:19.720
Practically the old have no very important advice to give the young. Their own experience has been so partial, and their lives have been such miserable failures, for private reasons, as they must believe. And it may be that they have some faith left which belies that experience, and they are only less young than they were.

16:19.720 --> 16:38.880
I have lived some thirty years on this planet, and I have yet to hear the first syllable of valuable or even earnest advice from my seniors. They have told me nothing, and probably cannot tell me anything to the purpose.

16:38.880 --> 17:01.020
Here is life, an experiment to a great extent untried by me, but it does not avail me that they have tried it. If I have any experience which I think valuable, I am sure to reflect that this my mentors said nothing about.

17:02.020 --> 17:10.600
One farmer says to me, You cannot live on vegetable food solely, for it furnishes nothing to make bones with.

17:10.600 --> 17:31.520
And so he religiously devotes a part of his day to supplying his system with the raw material of bones. Walking all the while he talks, behind his oxen, which, with vegetable-made bones, jerk him and his lumbering plough along in spite of every obstacle.

17:31.520 --> 17:46.840
Some things are really necessaries of life in some circles, the most helpless and diseased, which in others are luxuries merely, and in others still are entirely unknown.

17:47.700 --> 18:00.180
The whole ground of human life seems to some to have been gone over by their predecessors, both the heights and the valleys, and all things to have been cared for.

18:00.180 --> 18:01.580
According to Evelyn,

18:30.620 --> 18:41.760
undoubtedly, the very tedium and ennui which presume to have exhausted the variety and joys of life are as old as Adam.

18:41.760 --> 18:59.840
But man's capacities have never been measured, nor are we to judge of what he can do by any precedence. So little has been tried. Whatever have been thy failures hitherto,

19:01.140 --> 19:09.540
Be not afflicted, my child, for who shall assign to thee what thou hast left undone?

19:11.840 --> 19:25.860
We might try our lives by a thousand simple tests, as, for instance, that the same sun, which ripens my beans, illumines at once a system of earths like ours.

19:25.860 --> 19:40.720
If I had remembered this, it would have prevented some mistakes. This was not the light in which I hoed them. The stars are the apexes of what wonderful triangles.

19:40.720 --> 19:54.560
What distant and different beings in the various mansions of the universe are contemplating the same one at the same moment?

19:55.580 --> 20:14.920
Nature and human life are as various as our several constitutions. Who shall say what prospect life offers to another? Could a greater miracle take place than for us to look through each other's eyes for an instant?

20:14.920 --> 20:35.130
We should live in all the ages of the world in an hour. Aye, in all the worlds of the ages. History, poetry, mythology. I know of no reading of another's experience so startling and informing as this would be.

20:35.970 --> 20:47.430
The greater part of what my neighbours call good, I believe in my soul to be bad, and if I repent of anything it is very likely to be my good behaviour.

20:50.110 --> 21:12.070
What demon possessed me when I behaved so well? You may say the wisest thing you can, old man, you who have lived seventy years, not without honour of a kind. I hear an irresistible voice, which invites me away from all that.

21:12.070 --> 21:18.690
One generation abandons the enterprises of another like stranded vessels.

21:22.010 --> 21:33.830
I think that we may safely trust a good deal more than we do. We may waive just so much care of ourselves as we honestly bestow elsewhere.

21:34.930 --> 21:47.910
Nature is as well adapted to our weakness as to our strength. The incessant anxiety and strain of some is a well-nigh incurable form of disease.

21:47.910 --> 22:08.930
We are made to exaggerate the importance of what work we do, and yet how much is not done by us? Or what if we had been taken sick? How vigilant we are determined not to live by faith if we can avoid it.

22:08.930 --> 22:28.950
All the day long on the alert, at night we unwittingly say our prayers and commit ourselves to uncertainties. So thoroughly and sincerely are we compelled to live, reverencing our life, denying the possibility of change.

22:28.950 --> 22:50.590
This is the only way, we say, but there are as many ways as there can be drawn radii from one centre. All change is a miracle to contemplate, but it is a miracle which is taking place every instant.

22:51.590 --> 23:04.970
Confucius said, To know that we know what we know, and that we do not know what we do not know, that is true knowledge.

23:06.750 --> 23:21.450
When one man has reduced a fact of the imagination to be a fact to his understanding, I foresee that all men at length establish their lives on that basis.

23:21.450 --> 23:35.130
Let us consider for a moment what most of the trouble and anxiety which I have referred to is about, and how much it is necessary that we be troubled, or at least careful.

23:35.130 --> 24:03.870
It would be some advantage to live a primitive and frontier life, though in the midst of an outward civilization, if only to learn what are the gross necessaries of life, and what methods have been taken to obtain them, or even to look over the old day books of the merchants, to see what it was that men most commonly bought at the stores, what they stored, that is.

24:03.870 --> 24:22.030
What are the grossest groceries? For the improvements of ages have had but little influence on the essential laws of man's existence, as our skeletons, probably, are not to be distinguished from those of our ancestors.

24:22.890 --> 24:47.770
By the words necessary of life, I mean whatever of all that man obtains by his own exertions, has been from the first, or from long use, has become so important to human life that few, if any, whether from savageness or poverty or philosophy, ever attempt to do without it.

24:47.770 --> 25:05.190
To many creatures there is in this sense but one necessary of life, food. To the bison of the prairie it is a few inches of palatable grass, with water to drink, unless he seeks the shelter of the forest or the mountain's shadow.

25:06.290 --> 25:31.910
None of the brute creation requires more than food and shelter. The necessaries of life for man in this climate may, accurately enough, be distributed under the several heads of food, shelter, clothing, and fuel, for not till we have secured these are we prepared to entertain the true problems of life with freedom and a prospect of success.

25:31.910 --> 25:50.750
Man has invented not only houses but clothes and cooked food, and possibly from the accidental discovery of the warmth of fire and the consequent use of it, at first a luxury, arose the present necessity to sit by it.

25:50.750 --> 26:12.530
We observe cats and dogs acquiring the same second nature. By proper shelter and clothing we legitimately retain our own internal heat, but with an excess of these, or of fuel, that is, with an external heat greater than our own internal, may not cookery properly be said to begin?

26:14.050 --> 26:36.190
Darwin, the naturalist, says of the inhabitants of Tierra del Fuego, that while his own party, who were well clothed and sitting close to a fire, were far from too warm, these naked savages, who were farther off, were observed, to his great surprise, to be streaming with perspiration at undergoing such a roasting.

26:36.190 --> 26:46.310
So we are told the New Hollander goes naked with impunity, while the European shivers in his clothes.

26:47.590 --> 26:55.430
Is it impossible to combine the hardiness of these savages with the intellectualness of the civilized man?

26:55.430 --> 27:04.950
According to Leibig, man's body is a stove, and food the fuel which keeps up the internal combustion in the lungs.

27:04.950 --> 27:25.910
In cold weather we eat more, in warm less. The animal heat is the result of a slow combustion, and disease and death take place when this is too rapid, or for want of fuel, or from some defect in the draft the fire goes out.

27:26.610 --> 27:32.590
Of course the vital heat is not to be confounded with fire, but so much for analogy.

27:33.690 --> 28:02.330
It appears therefore, from the above list, that the expression animal life is nearly synonymous with the expression animal heat, for while food may be regarded as the fuel which keeps up the fire within us, and fuel serves only to prepare that food or to increase the warmth of our bodies by addition from without, shelter and clothing also serve only to retain the heat, thus generated and absorbed.

28:02.330 --> 28:10.750
The grand necessity then for our bodies is to keep warm, to keep the vital heat in us.

28:11.950 --> 28:30.610
What pains we accordingly take, not only with our food and clothing and shelter, but with our beds, which are our night-clothes, robbing the nests and breasts of birds to prepare the shelter within a shelter, as the mole has its bed of grass and leaves at the end of its burrow.

28:30.610 --> 28:45.070
The poor man is wont to complain that this is a cold world, and to cold, no less physical than social, we refer directly a great part of our ales.

28:45.070 --> 28:51.070
The summer, in some climates, make possible to man a sort of Alesian life.

28:51.870 --> 28:55.890
Fuel, except to cook his food, is then unnecessary.

28:56.650 --> 29:01.710
The sun is his fire, and many of the fruits are sufficiently cooked by its rays.

29:02.970 --> 29:10.670
While food generally is more various and more easily obtained, and clothing and shelter are wholly or half unnecessary.

29:11.330 --> 29:35.250
At the present day, and in this country, as I find by my own experience, a few implements, a knife, an axe, a spade, a wheel-barrow, etc., and for the studious, lamplight, stationary, and access to a few books, rank next to necessaries, and can all be obtained at a trifling cost.

29:35.250 --> 29:56.390
Yet some, not wise, go to the other side of the globe, to barbarous and unhealthy regions, and devote themselves to trade, for ten or twenty years, in order that they may live, that is keep comfortably warm, and die in New England at last.

29:57.160 --> 30:04.490
The luxuriously rich are not simply kept comfortably warm, but unnaturally hot.

30:05.410 --> 30:11.190
As I implied before, they are cooked, of course, à la mode.

